Flashing NVIDIA Jetson Xavier AGX with Official Image
___________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

This document describes the procedure to flash the NVIDIA Jetson Xavier AGX with the official Jetson Linux image provided by NVIDIA.
___________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Official documentation: NVIDIA Developer Guide â€“ Quick Start (https://docs.nvidia.com/jetson/archives/r34.1/DeveloperGuide/text/IN/QuickStart.html)
___________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

OS images: NVIDIA Jetson Linux Archive (https://developer.nvidia.com/embedded/jetson-linux-archive)
___________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Prerequisites:
	1. Host PC running Ubuntu 20.04 or 18.04 (x86_64 architecture)
	2. USB-C cable to connect Jetson to the host PC
	3. Downloaded Jetson Linux package from the Jetson Linux Archive (Driver Package (BSP) & Sample Root Filesystem)
	4. At least 25 GB of free disk space on the host machine
___________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Entering Recovery Mode:
	1. Power off the Jetson Xavier AGX
	2. Connect the device to the host PC via USB-C
	3. Press and hold the Force Recovery button
	4. While holding the button, press the Power button once
	5. Release the Force Recovery button

Confirm that the device is detected by running the following command on the host PC:

	$ lsusb

An NVIDIA Corp. device should appear in the list.
___________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Manual Flash (L4T, Ubuntu 20.04 LTS, GUI, Nvidia Drivers, etc):

	1. Extract the Jetson Linux package:
		$ sudo tar -xvzf Jetson_Linux_Rxx.x.x_aarch64.tbz2
		(after the process is done, open the directory)
		$ cd Linux_for_Tegra
	2. Extract the Root File System:
		$ cd Linux_for_Tegra/rootfs/
		$ sudo tar -xvzf ../../Tegra_Linux_Sample-Root-Filesystem_Rxx.x.x_aarch64.tbz2
	3. Applying binaries:
		$ cd ..
		$ sudo ./apply_binaries.sh

	(Make sure your device is in recovery mode)

	4. Run the flash command:
		$ sudo ./flash.sh ${BOARD} mmcblk0p1

	${BOARD}: 
		jetson-agx-xavier-devkit
		jetson-agx-xavier-industrial
		jetson-agx-orin-devkit
		jetson-xavier-nx-devkit
		jetson-xavier-nx-devkit-emmc


	Wait for the process to finish. The Jetson will reboot automatically with the newly flashed image.
___________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Minimal OS Manual Flash (L4T, Ubuntu 20.04):

	This option provides a completely barebone Ubuntu 20.04 installation, leaving out all unnecessary packages and GUI components to maximize performance and flexibility.

	
	Origin: "Minimized L4T" configuration for JetPack 5.x (https://nvidia-ai-iot.github.io/jetson-min-disk/jp5_minimal-l4t.html)


	1. Install Git, if haven't: 
		$ sudo apt update
		$ sudo apt install git -y
	2. Clone the nvidia-ai-iot repository:
		$ git clone https://github.com/NVIDIA-AI-IOT/jetson-min-disk
	3. Start the flashing process:
		$ cd jetson-min-disk
		$ ./scripts/prepare_l4t_dir.sh -b ${BOARD} -v r35.1.0 --flavor bone300 --l4tpkg k8
		$ cd Linux_for_Tegra
		$ sudo ./flash.sh ${BOARD} mmcblk0p1

	${BOARD}: 
		jetson-agx-xavier-devkit
		jetson-agx-xavier-industrial
		jetson-agx-orin-devkit
		jetson-xavier-nx-devkit
		jetson-xavier-nx-devkit-emmc


	Wait for the process to finish. The Jetson will reboot automatically with the newly flashed image. 
